TY  - JOUR
T1  - Technological and Regulatory Forces in the Developing Fusion of Financial-Services Competition
AU  - KANE, EDWARD J.
Y1  - 1984/07/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1984.tb03667.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 759
EP  - 772
VL  - 39
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1984.tb03667.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Product lines of traditionally heterogeneous financial institutions are rapidly fusing into a homogeneous blend. Institutions and market structures are reshaping themselves to lower the cost of serving customer demand for financial services. This paper contends that contemporary adaptations exploit scope economies rooted in technological change and deposit-insurance subsidies to innovative forms of risk-bearing. As they reorient work flows, financial firms are simultaneously restructuring their organizations to lower net burdens from government regulation. Alternative state and federal regulatory and legislative bodies compete vigorously for the regulatory business of developing institutional hybrids. Evolution of Federal Reserve policy toward ?nonbank banks? exemplifies the process.
ER  - 

